{{Infobox artist | name = Alexander (Oleksandr) Khvostenko-Khvostov | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1895|04|04}} | birth_place = Borisovka | death_date = {{Death date and age|1967|02|16|1895|04|04}} | death_place = [[Kiev]] | nationality = [[Russia]]/[[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] | spouse = | field = | training = [[Moscow School of Painting, Sculpture and Architecture]] | movement = [[Constructivism (art)|Constructivist]] | works = | patrons = | influenced by = | influenced = | awards = | elected = | website = | bgcolour = }} '''Alexander (Oleksandr) Khvostenko-Khvostov''' ({{lang-uk|Олександр Веніамінович Хвостенко-Хвостов}}) (1895–1967) was a [[Russia]]n/[[Ukraine|Ukrainian]]/[[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[avant-garde]] artist ([[Constructivism (art)|Constructivist]]), and [[stage designer]].
== Biography == Oleksandr Khvostenko-Khvostov was born in the village of Borisovka, now part of the [[Belgorod Oblast]] (Russia) on the 17 April (<small>4 April [[Adoption of the Gregorian calendar#Adoption in Eastern Europe|O.S]]</small>) 1895.
From 1907 to 1917 Alexander studied at the [[Moscow School of Painting, Sculpture and Architecture]] (MUZHZV). In 1917 he became a member of the ''[[Moscow Professional Union of Artists]]'' in [[Moscow]] together with [[Kazimir Malevich]], [[Aleksandra Ekster]], [[Vadym Meller]] and [[Vladimir Tatlin]]. From 1918 to 1919 he studied in the studio of Aleksandra Ekster in [[Kiev]], [[Ukraine]].
From 1920 to 1921 he designed posters and advertising boards. After 1920 he made numerous designs for ballets and operas in [[Kharkiv]] and Kiev, mainly in the [[Constructivism (art)|Constructivist]] style.
In 1926 he cooperated in the production of [[Sergei Prokofiev|Prokofiev]]'s ''[[Love for the three Oranges]]'' (one of his most experimental projects that was not performed) in Kharkiv. In 1927 he participated in the All-Ukrainian Exhibition ''Ten Years October'' together with [[Alexander Bogomazov]], [[Vadym Meller]], [[Vladimir Tatlin]], [[Victor Palmov]], [[Anatol Petrytsky]], [[Mark Epshtein]].
Oleksandr Khvostenko-Khvostov died 16 February 1967 in Kiev.
