'''Elliott Castro Tirado''' (February 17, 1949 – July 23, 2017) was a [[Santurce, San Juan, Puerto Rico]]-born [[sports commentator]], [[color commentator]], [[history of sports|sports historian]] and [[author]]. Castro was a commentator in [[Sports in Puerto Rico|major sports events in Puerto Rico]] as well as those related to Puerto Rican athletes such as the [[Olympics]], the [[Pan American Games]], and the [[Central American and Caribbean Games]].<ref>[http://www.ustream.tv/recorded/17278472 Entrevista a Elliott Castro], ustream.tv; accessed July 23, 2017.{{es icon}}</ref>
Castro has written several accounts of sports in Puerto Rico.<ref>[http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/2002/vol6n30/PRSportsBeat0630-en.html "Commonwealth Gives Puerto Rico A Sports Identity"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303193045/http://www.puertorico-herald.org/issues/2002/vol6n30/PRSportsBeat0630-en.html|date=2016-03-03}}, ''Puerto Rico Herald''; retrieved August 13, 2012.</ref> One of them he co-authored with Carmen Lidin and is titled ''Listos!: Puerto Rico En El Deporte Internacional (1930-2004)'' (English: Ready!: Puerto Rico in International Sports (1930-2004)).<ref>[http://www.bookfinder.com/author/elliott-castro-tirado ''Elliott Castro Tirado (Castro Tirado, Elliott)'']; retrieved August 13, 2012.</ref>
On July 23, 2017 Elliott Castro Tirado died of a heart attack in [[Bayamón, Puerto Rico]]. The February (22-25) 2018 edition of the "Festival de Claridad", a festival produced by an independent newspaper of the same name, is dedicated to him and his impact in the world of journalism.<ref>[https://www.metro.pr/pr/deportes/2017/07/23/fallece-analista-deportivo-elliot-castro.html Fallece el analista deportivo Elliott Castro], metro.pr; accessed July 24, 2017.{{es icon}}</ref>
