'''Ephraim Lipson''', or '''E. Lipson''' (1 September 1888, Sheffield – 22 April 1960) was a British [[economic history|economic historian]].
The son of a Jewish [[furniture]] dealer, Lipson attended [[Sheffield Royal Grammar School]] followed by [[Trinity College, Cambridge]], where he graduated with a First class degree in History.<ref>[http://zeffertt.co.uk/torvy/individual.php?pid=I1804&ged=zeff.ged Ephraim Lipson - I1804 - Individual Information - PhpGedView<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
He taught at [[Oxford University]] (as private [[tutor]], independent researcher) [[Cambridge University]] (1921–1931), [[Boston University]] (1932–1933), [[University of California]] (1933–).
== Literary works == * editor of the "''Economic History Review''" (1921–1934) (with [[Richard Henry Tawney]] (1880–1962), [[Michael Moïssey Postan]] (1899–1981), [[John Habakkuk|H. J. Habbakuk]], [[Economic History Society]]) * ''The economic history of England'', 3 Vols., 1915–1931 * ''Europe in the nineteenth century'', 1916 * ''The history of the English woollen and worsted industries'', 1921 * ''Increased production'', 1921 * ''The inventions'', 1934 * ''Europe'', 1914–1939 * ''A planned economy and free enterprise'', 1944
