'''Izz al-Din ibn Shaddad''' (1217-1285) ({{lang-ar|عز الدين بن شدّاد}}) was an [[Arab]] scholar and official for the [[Ayyubids]] from [[Aleppo]].
He is best known for his ''Al-a'laq al-khatira fi dhikr umara' al-Sham wa'l-Jazira'', a historical geography of [[Bilad al-Sham|Syria (al-Sham)]] and [[Upper Mesopotamia|Upper Mesopotamia (al-Jazira)]], which he wrote in exile in [[Egypt]] after the [[Mongol Empire|Mongols]] overran Syria. This work has been translated into French and published by [https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anne-Marie_Eddé Anne-Marie Eddé (on french Wikipedia)] as ''Description de la Syrie du Nord'' in Damascus in 1984.
He also wrote a biography of the [[Mamluks of Egypt|Mamluk]] ruler of Egypt, [[Baybars I]].
