{{Refimprove|date=October 2007}} {{Infobox military person | honorific_prefix = | name = Osman Gradaščević | honorific_suffix = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = | nickname = Osman-kapetan | birth_date = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}} if dead --> | birth_place = [[Bosnia Eyalet]], Ottoman Empire | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} death date first, then birth date --> | death_place = | placeofburial = | placeofburial_label = | placeofburial_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> | allegiance = {{flag|Ottoman Empire}} | branch = | serviceyears = 1765–1812 | rank = captain | unit = | commands = Captainy of [[Gradačac]] | battles = | battles_label = | awards = | memorials = | spouse = <!-- Add spouse if reliably sourced --> | relations = | signature = | signature_size = | signature_alt = | module = }} [[Image:Gradacac 15 - Rodna kuca Husejn kapetana.JPG|250px|thumb|The birth-house of his sons.]]
'''Osman Gradaščević''' ({{floruit}} 1765–died 1812) or '''Captain Osman''' (''Osman-kapetan''){{Cref2|a}} was an [[Bosnia Eyalet|Ottoman Bosnian]] captain of the military captaincy of [[Gradačac]], which he was in control of since 1765. During his rule he was one of the most powerful and richest captains in Bosnia. He was responsible for the construction of the White mosque in [[Modriča]] along with a nearby travelers inn, another mosque, and a [[madrassa]] with a fountain in [[Gračanica, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Gračanica]], as well as another madrassa in Gradačac. In 1808 he also carried on with the previously started renovation of the family castle in Gradačac.
Married to Melek-hanuma, Osman had six heirs. In order of birth they were Hamza, Murat, Osman, Muharrem, [[Husein Gradaščević|Husein]], and H. Bećir. After the death of captain [[Mehmed-beg Kulenović]] of Zvornik in 1806, Gradaščević received the title of [[Pasha]] for leading Bosnian forces against the [[First Serbian Uprising]] in 1812. The famed [[Samson Cerfberr of Medelsheim]] is known to have served under his command north of [[Gradačac]]. Osman Gradaščević died defending and aiding the captains of the Bosnian district of [[Zvornik]] against a Serbian incursion in 1812.
Known for his justice, he was killed by Djelal-ud-Din Pasha, Vizier of Travnik due to his opposing of reforms.<ref>{{cite book|author=Milovan Djilas|title=Njegos Poet, Prince, Bishop|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JZliAAAAMAAJ|year=1966|publisher=Harcourt, Brace & World|page=100}}</ref> His son Murat succeeded him as captain of Gradačac. Husein would go on to become one of the most famous figures in Bosnian history when he led the movement for Bosnian autonomy in 1831 and 1832.
==See also== *[[Ottoman Empire]] *[[Bosnia Eyalet]] *[[Selim III]] *[[Husein Gradaščević]] *[[Samson Cerfberr of Medelsheim]] *[[Ibrahim Bushati]]
==Annotations== {{Cnote2 Begin|liststyle=upper-alpha}} {{Cnote2|a| In [[Bosnian language|Bosnian]], his name is written ''Osman-kapetan Gradaščević'' (Осман-капетан Градашчевић), and scarcely as ''Osman-paša Gradaščević'' (Осман-паша Градашчевић). }} {{Cnote2 End}}
